            <p class="eyebrow">Common causes</p>
            <h2>Reasons a basement floor drain may be clogged</h2>
            <p>Basement floor drains experience clogs from debris buildup, sediment, or even tree root invasions. These issues can cause water backups, structural damage, mold, and mildew growth. Heavy rain and aging systems worsen conditions, making regular maintenance essential to prevent costly problems.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout-list">
            <div><strong>Debris and sediment buildup</strong><span>Laundry lint, hair, soap residue, and dirt accumulate over time, narrowing the drain and restricting water flow.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Tree root invasions</strong><span>Roots seek moisture and can infiltrate cracked or aging basement drain lines, causing severe blockages.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Heavy rainfall and storm surges</strong><span>Overwhelmed systems back up when the sewer line cannot handle the volume, especially with existing partial blockages.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Aging or deteriorating pipes</strong><span>Older cast iron or clay pipes corrode and develop cracks that catch debris and restrict flow.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Improper grading or pipe slope</strong><span>Poorly graded basement lines allow sediment to settle and create low spots that trap waste.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Cracked or collapsed pipe sections</strong><span>Soil shifting or foundation settlement can damage basement drain lines, leading to pooling or flooding.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

